data:
The "Europe - Our Future?" project aims to react to a recent wave of Eurosceptic attitudes in many European countries, including the United Kingdom. The last elections to the European Parliament meant a significant victory for various Eurosceptic or anti-European political parties. The global economic crisis and structural problems within the Eurozone left many people in precarious situations. Rightly or wrongly, the European Union is often blamed for this. The reasons for Euroscepticism are different in the UK, in Greece, in Italy or in the Czech Republic. However, there is a strong underlying crisis of confidence in the European integration.

The youth exchange has been initiated by young people from various European countries. Its aim is to raise awareness of young people about how the European institutions work, what they do and how they influence our lives. This will then form the basis for discussions about current issues in Europe and the future of the European integration.

The programme will use methodology of non-formal education. It will consist of simulation games, discussions, presentations, active workshops in smaller groups, plenary sessions, etc. It will be divided into three main parts:

1) Citizenship: activities aimed to discuss the topic of active citizenship, what it is and why is it important;
2) European Union: how it was created, how it works, how everybody can have an impact on the legislative process;
3) Future of Europe: visions of the Europe of the future;

We have invited 42 young participants from the United Kingdom, Poland, the Czech Republic, Italy, Romania and Slovakia. The project will also be a unique intercultural experience for the participants.
